commit.message:
Avoid using PyCollector - inherit from Module instead

PyCollector is technically private in pytest and might change/break.
The DescribeBlocks act like modules, so instead treat them as ones
directly.
Add some more attributes to setup
Increase development status
Add GitHub action status badge
Add linting and coverage to the tox configuration

Use GitHub action instead of Travis for testing

Also add deployment to GitHub action

Support Python 3.10

Note that this requires pytest 6.2.4 and
can currently be tested with 3.10rc1 only.
3.10 final will be released 2021-10-04.

Remove nonrelevant deprecation warning during tests

See https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest/issues/6936
Extend test matrix for pytest 6
Add Python 3.9 to classifiers list

Make markers consistent with pytest's defaults (#37)

* Add markers defined on describe function as markers
  of the describe block
* Add tests for advanced marker usage
* Fix assertion helper when only one warning is produced

This fixes an issue where markers could not be stacked
properly in a describe block. Additionally, this makes
it possible to have two separate @behaves_like blocks
to define different marks and parametrizations. Finally,
this significantly simplifies the processing of markers.

Make markers consistent with pytest's defaults (#37)

* Add markers defined on describe function as markers
  of the describe block
* Add tests for advanced marker usage
* Fix assertion helper when only one warning is produced

This fixes an issue where markers could not be stacked
properly in a describe block. Additionally, this makes
it possible to have two separate @behaves_like blocks
to define different marks and parametrizations. Finally,
this significantly simplifies the processing of markers.

commit.message:
Issue 32: Support list and tuple argnames for @pytest.mark.parametrize.

This commit affects the `pytestmark_name` method, which previously assumed that `mark.args[0]` was
always a str when converting the mark to a string.  However, `@pytest.mark.parametrize` permits an
`argnames` object which is a tuple or a list, for cases when you are parametrizing over multiple
variables.  This usage is now supported, and unit tests have been added.
